Let $\epsilon \in \R_{>0}$ be a [[Definition:Strictly Positive Real Number|strictly positive real number]]. By definition, $M$ is [[Definition:Totally Bounded Metric Space|totally bounded]] only if there exists a [[Definition:Finite Net|finite $\epsilon$-net]] for $M$. We use a [[Proof by Contraposition]]. To that end, suppose that there exists no [[Definition:Finite Net|finite $\epsilon$-net]] for $M$. The aim is to construct an [[Definition:Infinite Sequence|infinite sequence]] $\sequence {x_n} _{n \in \N}$ in $A$ that has no [[Definition:Convergent Sequence (Metric Space)|convergent]] [[Definition:Subsequence|subsequence]]. Suppose that $x_0, x_1, \ldots, x_r \in A$ have been defined such that: :$ orall m, n \in \set {0, 1, \ldots, r} : m 
e n \implies \map d {x_m, x_n} \ge \epsilon$ That is, any two [[Definition:Distinct Elements|distinct elements]] of $\set {x_0, x_1, \ldots, x_r}$ are at least $\epsilon$ apart. [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By hypothesis]], there exists no [[Definition:Finite Net|finite $\epsilon$-net]] for $M$. Specifically, $\set {x_0, x_1, \ldots, x_r}$ is therefore not an [[Definition:Net (Metric Space)|$\epsilon$-net]] for $M$. So, by definition of a [[Definition:Net (Metric Space)|$\epsilon$-net]]: :$\displaystyle A 
subseteq  igcup_{i \mathop = 0}^r \map {B_\epsilon} {x_i}$ where $\map {B_\epsilon} {x_i}$ denotes the [[Definition:Open Ball of Metric Space|open $\epsilon$-ball of $x_i$ in $M$]]. Thus there must exist $x_{r+1} \in A$ such that: :$\displaystyle x_{r+1} 
otin  igcup_{i \mathop = 0}^r \map {B_\epsilon} {x_i}$ That is: :$\exists x_{r+1} \in A:  orall m, n \in \set {0, 1, \ldots, r, r + 1} : m 
e n \implies \map d {x_m, x_n} \ge \epsilon$ Thus, by [[Principle of Mathematical Induction|induction]], the [[Definition:Infinite Sequence|infinite sequence]] $\sequence {x_n}$ in $A$ has been constructed such that: :$ orall m, n \in \N: m 
e n \implies \map d {x_m, x_n} \ge \epsilon$ Thus $\sequence {x_n}$ has no [[Definition:Cauchy Sequence (Metric Space)|Cauchy]] [[Definition:Subsequence|subsequence]]. Since a [[Convergent Sequence in Metric Space is Cauchy Sequence|convergent sequence is Cauchy]], it has no [[Definition:Convergent Sequence (Metric Space)|convergent]] [[Definition:Subsequence|subsequence]] either. Thus, by definition, $M$ is not [[Definition:Sequentially Compact Space|sequentially compact]]. From [[Rule of Transposition]], if $M$ is sequentially compact, then there exists no [[Definition:Finite Net|finite $\epsilon$-net]] for $M$. So if $M$ is sequentially compact, it is certainly not totally bounded. {{qed}}

