Let $AB$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $CD$. As $AB$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] itself, it follows that $AB$ is a [[Definition:Common Divisor of Real Numbers|common measure]] for $AB$ and $CD$. As no [[Definition:Strictly Positive Real Number|magnitude]] can [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] a smaller [[Definition:Strictly Positive Real Number|magnitude]], it follows that $AB$ is the [[Definition:Greatest Common Measure|greatest common measure]] of $AB$ and $CD].

Let $AB$ not [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $CD$. Let the less be continually subtracted in turn from the greater. We are given that $AB$ and $CD$ are [[Definition:Commensurable|commensurable]]. From [[Incommensurable Magnitudes do not Terminate in Euclid's Algorithm]], that which is left over will eventually [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] the one before it. Let $AB$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $ED$ and leave $EC$ less than $AB$. Let $EC$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $FB$ and leave $AF$ less than $EC$. Let $AF$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $CE$. Since: : $AF$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $CE$ and: : $CE$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $FB$ it follows that: : $AF$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] $FB$. But $AF$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] itself. Therefore $AF$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the whole of $AB$. But $AB$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $DE$. Therefore $AF$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $DE$. But $AB$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $CE$. Therefore $AF$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the whole of $CD$. Therefore $AF$ is a [[Definition:Common Divisor of Real Numbers|common measure]] for $AB$ and $CD].

Suppose there were some [[Definition:Strictly Positive Real Number|magnitude]] $G$ which is greater than $AF$ which is also a [[Definition:Common Divisor of Real Numbers|common measure]] for $AB$ and $CD]. Since: :$G$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $AB$ and: :$AB$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $ED$ it follows that: :$G$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $ED]. But $G$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the whole of $CD]. Therefore $G$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the remainder $CE]. But $CE$ [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $FB]. Therefore $G$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] $FB]. But $G$ also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the whole of $AB]. Therefore it also [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measures]] the remainder $AF]. But $G$ is greater than $AF$, and so cannot [[Definition:Divisor of Real Number|measure]] it. From this [[Proof by Contradiction|contradiction]] it follows that $G$ cannot be a [[Definition:Common Divisor of Real Numbers|common measure]] for $AB$ and $CD]. That is, $AF$ is the [[Definition:Greatest Common Measure|greatest common measure]] of $AB$ and $CD]. {{qed}} {{Euclid Note|3|X}}

