e 0\), then \(\map f {x, y} = \map f {y, x}\) for all \(y \in V\). Suppose \(f\) is not [[Definition:Symmetric Bilinear Form|symmetric]]. We show that \(\map f {u, u} = 0\) for all \(u \in V\). Let \(v, w \in V\) with \(\map f {v, w} 
e \map f {w, v}\). By \((2)\), \(\map f {v, v} = \map f {w, w} = 0\). Suppose \(u \in V\) with \(\map f {u, u} 
e 0\). By \((2)\), \(\map f {u, v} = \map f {v, u}\) and \(\map f {u, w} = \map f {w, u}\). By \((1)\), we have: :\( egin{cases} \map f {v, w} \, \map f {u, v} = \map f {v, u} \, \map f {w, v} \ \map f {w, v} \, \map f {u, w} = \map f {w, u} \, \map f {v, w} \end{cases}\). Because \(\map f {v, w} 
e \map f {w, v}\): :\( egin{cases} \map f {u, v} = \map f {v, u} = 0 \ \map f {u, w} = \map f {w, u} = 0 \end{cases}\). Because \(f\) is [[Definition:Bilinear Form|bilinear]], \(\map f {u + v, w} = \map f {v, w} 
e \map f {v, w} = \map f {u + v, w}\). By \((2)\), \(\map f {u + v, u + v} = 0\). Because \(f\) is [[Definition:Bilinear Form|bilinear]] and \(\map f {u, v} = \map f {v, u} = \map f {v, v} = 0\), \(\map f {u, u} = 0\). This [[Definition:Contradiction|contradicts]] the assumption \(\map f {u, u} 
e 0\). Thus \(f\) is [[Definition:Alternating Bilinear Form|alternating]]. {{qed}}

