statement:
Let $k$ be a field. Let $X$ be an algebraic space over $k$. The following are equivalent 
\begin{enumerate} 
\item $X$ is geometrically connected, 
\item for every finite separable field extension $k \subset k'$ the algebraic space $X_{k'}$ is connected. 
\end{enumerate}

Let $f : X 	o S$ be a morphism of schemes. The following are equivalent 
\begin{enumerate} 
\item $f$ is universally open, 
\item for every morphism $S' \to S$ which is locally of finite presentation the base change $X_{S'} \to S'$ is open, and 
\item for every $n$ the morphism $\mathbf{A}^n \times X \to \mathbf{A}^n \times S$ is open. 
\end{enumerate}

rationale:
Proof (by contradiction): Suppose there exist a₁, b₁ ∈ [a, b] with a₁ < b₁ such that f(a₁) < f(b₁). By the Intermediate Value Theorem, there exist a₂, b₂ such that a₁ < a₂ < b₂ < b₁, f(a₁) < f(a₂) < f(b₂) < f(b₁), and b₂ - a₂ < (b₁ - a₁)/2. Continuing this process, we obtain sequences {aₙ} and {bₙ} satisfying:
(i) a₁ < a₂ < ... < aₙ < ... < bₙ < ... < b₂ < b₁;
(ii) f(a₁) < f(a₂) < ... < f(aₙ) < ... < f(bₙ) < ... < f(b₂) < f(b₁);
(iii) bₙ - aₙ < (b - a)/2ⁿ → 0 as n → ∞.
By the Nested Interval Theorem, lim_{n→∞} aₙ = lim_{n→∞} bₙ = x₀. Clearly, x₀ is not a local extremum of f, contradicting the assumption.
